POLICE/MUNICIPAL COURTS - Ald. Clauss, Chairman (Cruts, Harrell, Jokerst)
- Consideration of amendments to Chapter 240, False Alarms, of the Municipal Code.
      Below is the proposed amendment to the City's Municipal Code related to Chapter 240 False Alarms for review, discussion, and consideration by the Board.

      Amending Section 240.020(B) False Alarm Charges

      B. Upon determination by the City Administrator or his or her designee that a false alarm has occurred and a service charge is due, the City shall send a notice to the alarm user of the determination and directing payment of the service charge to the City within thirty (30) days.

      City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner stated that this proposed amendment is to state that the City will send notices for false alarm service charges as the City collects the payment and the County is unable to change their forms. In response to questions from the Board, she clarified that exceptions can be made depending on the reason the alarm was activated and added that if an alarm user declines to pay, the user may be sent to court or have their business license revoked. Following discussion, Alderwoman Clauss made a motion to forward the proposed amendments as drafted to the August Board meeting. The motion was seconded by Alderman Cruts. Upon a vote being taken, it was announced that the motion passed unanimously by the Committee.

PERSONNEL - Ald. Huels, Chairman (Cruts, Wisbrock, Jokerst)
- Discussion regarding Annual Performance Evaluations.
      At the July 13th Board of Aldermen Committee meeting, it was suggested to continue to the August Board of Aldermen Committee meeting the Annual Performance Evaluations to allow the Board time to submit written suggestions for further discussion so that amendments can be formalized before time to utilize the forms.

      Traditionally, annual merit-based increases are based on performance evaluations. As any amendments will need to be discussed, approved, and completed by the end of August at the latest - to ensure that forms are updated and distributed to Supervisors to allow proper time to complete and submit by the required October 31st deadline.

      To help the Board further review, analyze, and submit suggestions; copies of the Evaluation Policy, approved by the Board in September 2022, and the current and draft evaluation forms the Board has been reviewing were sent to the Board via email on July 18th.

      Below are suggestions that have been received to date:

      1. suggestion received:
         Non-supervisory:
         Not to remove "Exceeds" from Quality & Quantity of Work and Initiative categories only - as it allows an employee to attain a favorable rating, if they do not perform as well in other areas.

         Supervisory:
         Not to remove "Exceeds" from Supervision & Leadership and Planning and Organizational Management categories only - as it allows an employee to attain a favorable rating, if they do not perform as well in other areas.

         Incorporate Responsibility & Initiative into Planning and Organizational Management category.

      2. suggestion received:
         Remove "Exceeds" from rating, add text areas for written information under Performance Goals - "area person exceeds" and "examples where employee went above and beyond".
         Change "Does Not Meet" to "NI-Needs Improvement"
         Also, need to provide "Does Well" or "Area to Improve" in comments and examples for each category.

      3. suggestion received:
         Both evaluations are acceptable. The newer version is more concise and perhaps easier for some people to complete.

         As far as the levels of competence, I feel it is important to keep all three. Does Not Meet allows for the employee to be put on notice and given the tools and opportunity to come to an acceptable level. Meet Expectations is just that, they are doing the job--average. Exceeds Expectations is for those that give something extra to their job--above average. I believe there has been an atmosphere/expectation created by the leadership and supervisors that employees go that extra step and do more than just their "job description". The employees who go beyond expectations deserve an additional perk. Without the incentive, I would wonder why anyone would go the extra mile or foot.

      4. suggestion received:
         In response, I believe our current system is not effective and have relayed that on many occasions. I have tried to educate myself as the rater best I could. This comes after time. Not many of us have had the experience in our professional careers. So, in this setting, we may be ineffective. That's why, for the sake of the employee, simpler is better.

         I have stated many times I'm not comfortable granting an exceeds expectations in any case. I hire with the expectation of the individual meeting our standards.

         There is no gauge between unsatisfactory and meets and between meets and exceeds. There needs to be much more discussion and fine-tuning. Simpler is better.

      City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner stated that since there has been no consensus regarding proposed amendments, a meeting with the Mayor, Personnel Chair, and City Administrator is proposed to discuss the evaluation forms, and she would like to continue the matter to the next Committee meeting.

- Discussion regarding amendments to Section 7.1.3, Pay for New Employees, of the City's Personnel Manual
      To follow up on recent discussions to possibly allow the Public Works Director to hire employees in at a higher rate of pay than the base pay without needing approval by the Board (which can delay making an offer to a candidate for employment), Staff offers the following for consideration:

      Step 1. Amend Section 7.1.3 of the Personnel Manual as italicized and underlined below. This would only be on a temporary basis and any hire above base pay would still require approval by the Mayor, Personnel Chairman, and City Administrator. (Note: this amendment would require approval via an Ordinance).

      Step 2. After approving the above, the Board could then approve a motion to "allow the Public Works Director to hire PW Maintenance Worker I positions at a rate over the base pay, but not to exceed $____, based on qualifications. This approval is temporary and shall not exceed _ months and can only be extended by a vote of the Board."

      7.1.3 Pay for New Employees

      A new Employee shall be hired within the Pay Scale for the job position. Generally, he/she shall be hired at the minimum pay within that range, unless he/she possesses the experience and qualifications that warrant advanced pay within the Pay Scale.

      The Board must approve paying any new hire above the minimum pay within the Pay Scale. New Employees will be reviewed at the end of their Probationary Periods for performance evaluation; however, merit increase review will be performed at the annual scheduled review.

      The Public Works Director, with the approval of the Mayor, Chairperson of the Personnel Committee, and the City Administrator may offer hiring a candidate to Maintenance Worker I position at $1.00 above base pay if the candidate already possesses a Commercial Driver's License (CDL). (In the absence of one of the three named positions, the Board must approve for employment.)

      Notwithstanding the above, the Board may approve by motion at a Committee Meeting or Board Meeting the ability for a Department Head, on a temporary basis, to hire new Employees above the minimum pay, with the approval of the Mayor and Chairperson of the Personnel Committee, and City Administrator in lieu of Board approval.

      Details were given regarding the proposed changes that would allow a Department Head to hire above the minimum pay on a temporary basis with the approval of the Mayor, Chairperson, and City Administrator. It was mentioned that this would help to avoid the loss of potential employees as the offer could be made without having to wait for the next Board meeting for approval.

      It was discussed that this is a good compromise to hopefully aid the Public Works Director in hiring new employees and that the Board always has the ability to change the policy if it doesn't appear to be working.

      Following discussion, Alderwoman Huels made a motion to forward the request for amendments to the personnel manual to the August Board meeting and to allow Public Works Director Dan Howard the ability to offer up to $19 per hour for a term of 6 months. The motion was seconded by Alderman Wisbrock, and upon the vote being taken, it was announced the motion was approved unanimously.


